      <hedline>
        <hl1>Anti-Soviet Liberals</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Arthur Schlesinger Jr letter says he has rarely read so 'daffy' a letter as May 11 missive suggesting that American liberals did not support resistance to Soviet Communism during Cold War</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I have rarely read so daffy a letter as the one published on May 11 under the headline ''Liberals in Denial.'' Of course Anthony Lewis (column, May 6) was right in saying that the ''overwhelming majority of liberal Americans supported the West's staunch and successful resistance to Soviet Communism.''</p>
        <p>That was true from the start; it is why, when the cold war had barely begun, American liberals backed Harry S. Truman and opposed Henry A. Wallace in 1948.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I have rarely read so daffy a letter as the one published on May 11 under the headline ''Liberals in Denial.'' Of course Anthony Lewis (column, May 6) was right in saying that the ''overwhelming majority of liberal Americans supported the West's staunch and successful resistance to Soviet Communism.''</p>
        <p>That was true from the start; it is why, when the cold war had barely begun, American liberals backed Harry S. Truman and opposed Henry A. Wallace in 1948.</p>
        <p>I have no idea what liberals the letter writer associates with, but no liberal of my acquaintance has ever been heard to say, ''Nobody won the cold war.''</p>
        <p>ARTHUR SCHLESINGER JR.  New York, May 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
